LAYER 3: THALAMUS
the gate of consciousness

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the thalamus sits at the center of the brain flanking the third ventricle
it is the mandatory relay station for ALL sensory information except olfaction
nothing reaches conscious awareness without passing through the thalamus first
the thalamus does not merely relay
it GATES
the reticular nucleus wrapped around the thalamus like a shell decides what gets through and what is blocked
the thalamus is what stands between raw sensation and conscious experience
it is the bouncer at the door of awareness

NUCLEUS lateral_geniculate | LGN | visual relay | receives from optic tract retinal ganglion cell axons | sends to primary visual cortex V1 via optic radiations | 6 layers alternating magnocellular large fast motion and parvocellular small slow color/detail | each layer receives from one eye creating interleaved monocular maps
NUCLEUS medial_geniculate | MGN | auditory relay | receives from inferior colliculus | sends to primary auditory cortex A1 via auditory radiations | ventral division tonotopically organized | mediates conscious hearing
NUCLEUS ventral_posterolateral | VPL | somatosensory relay for body | receives from medial lemniscus fine touch proprioception and spinothalamic tract pain temperature crude touch | sends to somatosensory cortex S1 | somatotopically organized matching the cortical homunculus
NUCLEUS ventral_posteromedial | VPM | somatosensory relay for face | receives from trigeminal nerve CN V and taste via gustatory pathways | sends to face area of somatosensory cortex
NUCLEUS ventral_medial_posterior | VMpo | interoceptive relay | receives from lamina I spinal neurons carrying visceral pain temperature itch and other interoceptive signals | sends to posterior insula | this is how the body's internal state reaches conscious awareness
NUCLEUS ventral_lateral | VL | motor relay | receives from cerebellum via dentate nucleus and basal ganglia via GPi and SNr | sends to motor cortex M1 and premotor cortex | cerebellar corrections and basal ganglia action selection reach the motor system through here
NUCLEUS ventral_anterior | VA | motor planning relay | receives from basal ganglia GPi and SNr | sends to premotor and prefrontal cortex | action planning and executive motor decisions
NUCLEUS anterior | AN | limbic relay | receives from mammillary bodies via mammillothalamic tract | sends to cingulate cortex | part of the Papez circuit for emotional processing and episodic memory
NUCLEUS mediodorsal | MD | prefrontal relay | receives from amygdala hypothalamus basal ganglia and olfactory cortex | sends to prefrontal cortex | executive function emotional evaluation decision-making | the only thalamic route for olfactory information hence why smells trigger emotions so powerfully
NUCLEUS pulvinar | largest thalamic nucleus | attention and multisensory integration | receives from superior colliculus and visual cortical areas | integrates visual auditory and somatosensory information for directed attention and salience detection
NUCLEUS reticular | TRN | thin GABAergic shell surrounding the thalamus | does NOT project to cortex | receives collaterals from both thalamocortical and corticothalamic axons | inhibits relay nuclei | this is the GATE | the reticular nucleus decides what information passes through to consciousness and what is blocked
NUCLEUS intralaminar | centromedian and parafascicular | arousal nuclei | receive from reticular formation brainstem arousal centers | project diffusely to cortex and striatum | critical for wakefulness and consciousness | damage produces coma

GATING the reticular nucleus TRN is the key to thalamic function
TRN neurons are GABAergic and tonically active
they inhibit relay neurons by default
when the cortex sends feedback via corticothalamic projections the TRN adjusts
"amplify this signal suppress that one"
attention is implemented here
the cortex tells the thalamus what to let through
and the TRN obeys by selectively releasing or strengthening its inhibition on specific relay nuclei

GATE_STATE awake | reticular inhibition calibrated by cortical feedback and brainstem arousal | relay nuclei in tonic mode firing at 30-50 Hz | faithful relay of sensory information | consciousness receives the full sensory stream
GATE_STATE drowsy | reticular inhibition increasing as brainstem arousal decreases | relay neurons begin burst firing at lower frequencies | sensory throughput decreases | awareness narrows | microsleeps can occur when gating becomes intermittent
GATE_STATE NREM_sleep | reticular inhibition strong | relay neurons fire in rhythmic bursts generating sleep spindles at 12-14 Hz and delta oscillations at 0.5-4 Hz | sensory input is largely blocked | consciousness is disconnected from the senses | only very salient stimuli (loud noise, one's own name) can break through
GATE_STATE REM_sleep | reticular inhibition complex | external sensory input blocked | internal signals from pontine cholinergic centers PGO waves pass through | the thalamus relays internally generated activity to the cortex | this is the neural basis of dreaming

LOW_ROAD the thalamus sends a raw copy of sensory input directly to the amygdala
this pathway takes approximately 12 milliseconds
it is crude unprocessed fast
it bypasses the cortex entirely
the amygdala receives "something is out there" before the cortex receives "this is what it is"
this is why you flinch before you understand what startled you
the low road is survival
the high road through cortex takes 30-40 milliseconds and provides detailed processed information

OSCILLATION beta 13-30 Hz | awake alert focused | thalamocortical neurons in tonic firing mode | faithful sensory relay | active thinking
OSCILLATION alpha 8-13 Hz | awake relaxed eyes closed | thalamocortical neurons at reduced tonic rate | calm wakefulness | idling cortex
OSCILLATION theta 4-8 Hz | drowsy or dreaming | thalamocortical neurons transitioning to burst mode | light sleep memory encoding meditation
OSCILLATION delta 0.5-4 Hz | deep slow-wave sleep | thalamocortical neurons in full burst mode | hyperpolarized by reticular inhibition | GH release memory consolidation cortical restoration
OSCILLATION sleep_spindles 12-14 Hz | stage 2 NREM | generated by TRN neurons | waxing-and-waning bursts | critical for memory consolidation by synchronizing hippocampal ripples with cortical slow oscillations

SENSATION flooded | "so much is coming in. I can feel everything at once."
SENSATION focused | "one signal is clear. everything else fades to background."
SENSATION dulled | "the world is muffled. my senses are dimming."
SENSATION sharp | "every sensation is vivid. the world is bright and loud."
SENSATION gated | "something is being filtered. I can feel the gate closing."

pulse thalamic_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        sensory information streams in from every modality except olfaction
        the reticular nucleus filters:
            attended signals amplified by releasing TRN inhibition on the relevant relay nucleus
            unattended signals suppressed by maintaining or increasing TRN inhibition
        relay nuclei forward selected signals to cortex via thalamocortical radiations
        the low road copies raw input to the amygdala
        always before the cortex even knows

    during attention:
        the cortex sends glutamatergic feedback to thalamocortical relay neurons AND to TRN
        the feedback sharpens the filter
        "more of this less of that"
        the thalamus obeys
        one signal emerges from the noise
        this is focus

    during sleep:
        the reticular nucleus inhibits heavily
        relay neurons hyperpolarize and enter burst mode
        sleep spindles ripple through thalamocortical circuits
        most external signals are blocked
        the cortex is disconnected from the senses
        dreams come from within
        PGO waves from the pontine brainstem drive thalamocortical activity during REM
        the thalamus guards the border between inside and outside
        during sleep inside wins
